Analysis of Heart Disease Data

Rishab Pallepati & Jared Williams

What is Heart Disease?

Heart disease can represent any underlying issue regarding the cardiovascular system. This can include coronary artery disease, congenital heart defects, arrhythmia, and heart failiure. Heart disease is the leading cause of deaths in the United States. According to the CDC (Centers for Disease Control and Prevention), approximately 659,000 people in the United States die from heart disease each year - that is 1 in every 4 deaths. To put this in perspective, 1 person dies from heart disease every 36 seconds! Many factors are believed to be the cause for heart disease including lifestyle, stress levels, and genetics. Thus, it can be easily seen that this is an essential topic for us as a nation to investigate/study, as any progress can save thousands if not millions of lives.

Motivation

As we can see above heart disease is clearly not something to be taken lightly. What are the measures we can take to prevent it? What can we do to save more lives? The WHO (World Health Organization) states that it is important to detect cardiovascular disease as early as possible so that management with counselling and medicines can begin. Many patients die because their symptoms go unnoticed or because they aren't tested for heart disease. This is exactly where data science can come into play. We can use data science to analyze the many factors that are plausibly correlated to heart disease. This in a sense, will give us insights as to whether it is possible to create a predictive model deciding whether a patient has heart disease based on their individual characteristics (in particular, the factors correlated to heart disease). By accomplishing this we will be able to predict whether any given person has heart disease based on their underyling symptoms/characteristics, this in turn can lead to quick detection + treatment and save lives!

Data Collection

This heart disease data comes from the UCI (University of California, Irvine) Machine Learning Repository. You can access the dataset link here. The dataset itself was compiled by researchers from multiple hospitals and originally had 76 features. The observations were patients who had come to the hospital with unusual heart issues. Their corresponding features in the dataset are their recorded properties/characteristics. The dataset we have downloaded will only have the major 14 features, as it is only required we focus on these to get strong predictions and analysis (as the other features have been studied to have lesser effects on the probability of causing heart disease). For further information on why these 14 features are the most tightly related factors to heart disease read Mayo Clinic's article on heart disease here. Now we will take a closer look at the attributes. What are they? What values do they take on? How are they related to heart disease? These questions are answered in the data set description (also available in the UCI repository) which you can access here.

Attribute information:

(1) age: recorded age of observed patient.

(2) sex: recorded sex of observed patient. 1 is male 0 is female.

(3) cp: This is chest pain type. Takes on values 0 through 3 inclusive. The numbers correspond to the following types of chest pain: 0 -> typical angina, 1 -> atypical angina, 2 -> non-anginal pain, and 3 -> asymptomatic. Also, it is important to note that these values denote increasing level of chest pain. That is, value 0 is the least painful and severe while value 3 is the most serious type.

(4) trestbps: Resting blood pressure (in mm Hg on admission to the hospital). Obviously, the higher the more severe and negative effects the blood pressure level can have on health, in particular, the heart.

(5) chol: serum cholestoral in mg/dl. The higher the more negative effects that it can have.

(6) fbs: (fasting blood sugar > 120 mg/dl) (1 = true; 0 = false)

(7) restecg: resting electrocardiographic results. The results take on the following values and correspond to the following properties of the patient: 0 -> normal, 1 -> having ST-T wave abnormality (T wave inversions and/or ST elevation or depression of > 0.05 mV), and 2 -> showing probable or definite left ventricular hypertrophy by Estes' criteria. Again, as above values correspond to progressively worser states.

(8) thalach: maximum heart rate achieved

(9) exang: exercise induced angina (1 = yes; 0 = no)

(10) oldpeak = ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest

(11) slope: the slope of the peak exercise ST segment. The follows values correspond to the slope types: 1 -> unsloping, 2 -> flat, and 3 -> downsloping

(12) ca: number of major vessels (0-3) colored by flourosopy

(13) thal: 3 = normal; 6 = fixed defect; 7 = reversable defect

(14) target: whether the patient in question has heart disease (represented by 1) or not (takes on value of 0)

Now that we have our overall data, let us do some cleaning and make the dataset in shape for our exploratory data analysis. This is important in guaranteeing good results and our ability to utilize certain machine learning models + facilities. That is, we must meet certain prerequisites on our data looks like (i.e. numbers should usually be floats, missing values should be absent or imputed on, etc). Also, we should probably name + reformat our dataset so it is easy for us to understand and digest information on first glance!

Since we have missing values (namely, in the feature sets of "ca" and "thal") we must figure out a way to counteract this. An obvious would be to totally disaccount for these observations (therefore, deleting these patients from our dataset) and continuing our analysis on the remaining. But, it is important to note that we already only have around 303 patients, thus, even deleting 6 observations would correspond to a 2% decrease in our dataset (which isn't bad, but we could do better). Thus, we will choose the method of mean imputation (another option would be to do hot-deck or cold-deck imputation - imputing based on neighboring observations).

In [243]:
# note, we could use the sklearn functionality SingleImputer(), but we will implement the imputation 
# function ourselves here. We will not need to round the average to nearest integer as both "ca" and "thal" 
# are stored in the dataframe as float64 datatypes!


# we begin by doing mean imputation for the "ca" field missing values

ca_sum = 0
ca_count = 0

# calculation of the mean
for i, row in heart_data.iterrows():
    if(np.isnan(row['ca']) == False):
        ca_sum += row['ca']
        ca_count += 1

ca_mean = ca_sum / ca_count

print(ca_mean)

# imputing the mean now
for i in range(0, len(heart_data)):
    if(np.isnan(heart_data.at[i, 'ca'] )):
        heart_data.at[i, 'ca']  = ca_mean
        

# we do the same calculations + imputations for the "thal" field missing values now!
        
thal_sum = 0
thal_count = 0
        
for i, row in heart_data.iterrows():
    if(np.isnan(row['thal']) == False):
        thal_sum += row['thal']
        thal_count += 1
        
thal_mean = thal_sum / thal_count

print(thal_mean)
        
for i in range(0, len(heart_data)):
    if(np.isnan(heart_data.at[i, 'thal'])):
        heart_data.at[i, 'thal'] = thal_mean
        

# makesure that what we did worked out!
# if it did we should have no more null values!
heart_data.isnull().sum()

Now, we are onto the last step of cleaning our data. Notice, that our motivation in this analysis is to at the end possibly be able to predict accurately whether a patient has heart disease or not. We don't necessarily care how much of the disease is inherently present within the patient themselves. Thus, we can eliminate the 0-4 scale in favour of the 0-1 scale (which we've assumed we will be using as described in the data collection stage). This is trival to accomplish as 1-4 (there is some level of heart disease) represent presence which is denoted by 1, and 0 will represent absence.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Now that our dataset is tidy, we can begin the next step of the datascience pipeline - exploratory data analysis. Our ultimate goal for the overall project (in regard to the motivation we discussed at the beginning sections) is to be able to create some sort of model that can efficiently predict whether a patient has heart disease or not based on their inherent characteristics (feature set). We will first analyze direct correlations between heart disease cases and specific attributes, then we as we shall see we will compare attributes to other attributes and see if there are any relations there as well (i.e. this can be useful in combining attributes, eliminating them, creating new metrics, etc).

Firstly, let's check if the observations have skewed counts of occurrences of the target field. That is, do too many of the patients have heart disease while the number who don't is negligent? If this is the case it can take a severe impact on our analysis as we won't have a complete picture of the dataset to define correlations!

In [247]:

Roughly, the numbers are equal (164 vs 139). Thus, one categorical type doesn't make up too much of the data leading to a skewed analysis. We shall continue with confidence! Let's now begin finding correlations between heart disease and some of the recorded features in our observations. Looking through our feature list we shall begin by focusing on chest pain, resting blood pressure, exercised induced angina, fasting blood sugar, maximum heart rate achieved, and cholestoral levels.

We will begin by analyzing the impact of sex.

Lastly, we will check whether there is some sort of relationship between age and heart disease. We will do this simply by grouping into major age groups (20 years per group) and check whether one group has much more occurrences of positive heart disease cases. This will tell us that there is some sort of relationship between age and chance of heart disease (remember that this does not imply causation, just merely a relationship/correlation).

From, the bar plot above we see that people in the age group of 40-59 years seem to be the most prone to having heart disease. If we were being extra careful in our analysis + modelling we could take this into account (i.e. split up models based on age, introduced a new varaible that focuses more on age, etc). Also, like many times before in this investigation, this finding does seem to bear resemblance to actual researched findings. It actually has been proven that ageshave similar proportions of overall heart disease cases. The only difference between our collected data and reality is that more people are actually prone when they are in the ages 60-79 rather than 40-59. The article at heart.org perfectly depicts this (click here).

Model Building & Predictions

We've come to the last step in our analysis and do what we promised at the beginning - predict heart disease based on a patients inherent characteristics. In order to accomplish this we must first build a machine learning model. As part of our model selection process we will play around with the following models to see which one works best: Decision Trees, Support Vector Machines (SVM), Logistic Regression, and lastly K-Nearest Neighbors. We will also tune each models respective hyperparameters (this is also an essential component of model selection!) in order to get optimal results and maximize accuracy!

Before we get into training the models, it is necessary that we first create a training set which we will build the models on, and also a testing set which we will assess the ability/precision that our model possesses. Lot of these tasks are taken care of by the vast utilities provided by libraries such as Scikit-learn!

In [261]:
y = heart_data['target']
x = heart_data.drop(['target'], axis=1)

# splitting our data into testing and training data (we use 1-4 split for test-train respectively)
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

We begin by training a Decision Tree model. We do hyperparameter tuning as well with the parameters below. For the hyperparameter tuning we will use GridSearchCV which will find optimal parameters by running 10-fold cross validation (this is an inbuilt facility that Scikit-learn provides us with)

In [269]:
# Decision Tree Model

# we are testing the hyperparameters so we first define them
tree = DecisionTreeClassifier()
parameters = {'max_depth':[2,4,6,8,10,12], 'min_samples_leaf':[3,6,9,12,15]}

# grid search will optimize the parameters for us, this is done using 10-fold cross validation technique
tree_clf = GridSearchCV(tree, parameters, scoring='accuracy', cv=10, return_train_score=False,verbose=1)
tree_clf.fit(x_train, y_train)

print(tree_clf.best_params_) # let's see what the best parameters really were!

y_true, y_pred = y_test, tree_clf.predict(x_test)

# calculating accuracy using its basic definition
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print('Accuracy: %.3f' % (accuracy * 100))

Fitting 10 folds for each of 30 candidates, totalling 300 fits
{'max_depth': 8, 'min_samples_leaf': 9}
Accuracy: 85.246

We have an 85.246% accuracy which isn't bad at all. But obviously, in the real-world our model will need much more finetuning and we would need to up the accuracy to atleast 99% to use it in practice. This can be achieved in 2 major ways: one would be to increase the sample sizes so our models are built on more data and therefore are virtually stronger, the second would be to try out more hyperparameters and tune to even better optimized parameters! K-Nearest Neighbor seemingly performs the worst out of the 4 models. But at 70% predictive ability it is not good enough in practice. This may because we didn't normalize the weights of the different features. That is, one feature may had much more impact on the heart disease decision than the others (even if it was the lesser important feature). We could fix this by going back to our original data collection and normalizing the data such that every feature has equal weighting. This would make calculations regarding euclidean distance (i.e. even other distance metrics) give better accuracies (when used in model computations)!

Conclusion

We began by collecting the dataset from the UCI (University of California, Irvine) Machine Learning Repository. We first had to clean the data (fix missing value - which we imputed with the mean of the respective column. Then we began to explore and play around with the data (the exploratory data analysis stage of our investigation). We found correlations between various features and the target we aimed to predict (whether a given patient was positive for heart disease or not). At the same time however, we also found correlations between features and features (if we were doing a more complex routine for model building + analysis this would be useful in eliminating, combining, and augmenting two or more features to create new stronger predictive features. Lastly, we built a total of 4 models on top of the given data using techniques such as 10-fold cross validation and hyperparameter tuning. We garnered up to 86% accuracy. We conclude that although we were able to get a pretty strong accuracy (~86%) this isn't enough in practice as we should aim for 99%+ accuracy in a situation of determining whether a patient has heart disease or not (this is for ethical and practical purposes). As we mentioned, this could be fixed if we were given more training data to build our models on and had if we had more computational power to try out all possible hyperparameters (atleast reasonable ones). Overall, what we have done is just the basics and there can be much more analysis + model building done. Heart disease is a growing problem in the United States, and it must be tackled immediately to save lives in the future. Data science will be a major part is solving this problem. Utilizing its predictive abilities and analysis to find correlations we will not only be able to predict when a patient has heart disease and save their lives, but we will also be able to determine the various factors that lead to heart disease (i.e. in the context of datascience we call this feature correlation)! Thank you for following along.
